st Liberal Essentialisms and toward Radical Neighbourliness in Rural Anti-racism -- t11 The Work of Neighbours: A Rural Ethos for Reconciliation -- tConclusion -- tContributors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis collection challenges misconceptions that rural Canada is a bastion of intolerance. While examining the extent and nature of contemporary cultural and religious discrimination in rural Canadian communities, the editors and contributors explore the many efforts by rural citizens, community groups, and municipalities to counter intolerance, build inclusive communities, and become better neighbours. Throughout, scholars and community leaders focus on building new understandings, language, and ways of thinking about diversity and inclusion that will resonate with rural people. Scholars of rural studies will find this book useful as will rural community leaders and community organizers. Contributors: Clark Banack, Ray Bollman, Claudine Bonner, Corina Borri-Anadon, Jen Budney, Michael Corbett, Roger Epp, Murray Fulton, Stacey Haugen, Phil Henderson, Sivane Hirsch, Michelle Lam, Coleen Lynch, Aasa Marshall, Darcy Overland, Trista Pewapisconias, Dionne Pohler, Samuel Reimer, Jennifer Tinkham, Kyle White  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity lifezCanada. 0aCultural pluralismzCanada. 0aSocial integrationzCanada. 0aTolerationzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Rural.2bisacsh  aInclusive.  aanti-racism.  aco-operative.  acultural and religious minorities.  adiversity.  aeducation.  aequity.  afaith.  aimmigrant.  ainclusion.  aneighbor.  aneighbourliness.  anewcomer.  arefugee. 